# SAP Go-Live Operational Maturity Framework (GOMF)

A practical and executive-oriented framework to evaluate, structure, and evolve SAP go-live execution capabilities across governance, operational readiness, cutover orchestration, hypercare, stabilization, and predictive operational control.

## SAP Go-Live Operational Maturity Framework (GOMF)

<p align="center">
  <img src="images/sap-go-live-operational-maturity-framework.png" alt="SAP Go-Live Operational Maturity Framework Diagram">
</p>

<p align="center">
  <em>
    From Strategy to Stabilization. Execute with Control. Decide with Confidence.
  </em>
</p>

---

# Why This Framework Exists

Most SAP programs treat go-live as a technical milestone.

High-performing organizations treat go-live as an operational capability.

The difference between a successful deployment and a prolonged stabilization crisis is rarely technical alone. It is usually determined by:
- governance maturity
- operational discipline
- executive visibility
- readiness management
- escalation effectiveness
- decision-making quality under pressure

This framework was created to help organizations move beyond reactive deployments and evolve toward predictive and AI-assisted go-live governance.

---

# Core Philosophy

A technically completed deployment does not necessarily mean a successful go-live.

Real success is measured by:
- operational stability
- business continuity
- defect containment
- recovery capability
- hypercare efficiency
- executive control
- long-term sustainability

Go-live maturity is therefore not a project phase.

It is an organizational capability.

---

# The 5 Levels of Go-Live Maturity

| Level | Name | Description |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Reactive | Hero-driven execution with unstable governance |
| 2 | Structured | Formal planning and basic process control |
| 3 | Controlled | Integrated operational governance and rehearsed execution |
| 4 | Predictive | Metrics-driven execution with risk forecasting |
| 5 | Adaptive | AI-assisted orchestration and autonomous governance |

---

# Level 1 — Reactive

## Characteristics
- Cutover managed through spreadsheets
- Heavy dependency on key individuals
- No integrated command structure
- Informal escalation paths
- Limited executive visibility

## Common Symptoms
- Endless war rooms
- Confusion during downtime windows
- Unclear ownership
- High incident reopening rates
- Hypercare instability

---

# Level 2 — Structured

## Characteristics
- Formal cutover plan exists
- Freeze governance partially implemented
- Basic checkpoint controls
- Initial risk management discipline

## Limitations
- Weak cross-stream coordination
- Limited operational telemetry
- Reactive issue escalation
- Hypercare still unstable

---

# Level 3 — Controlled

## Characteristics
- Multiple rehearsal cycles
- Integrated command center
- Formal hypercare governance
- Structured escalation model
- Executive reporting cadence

## Capabilities
- Controlled cutover execution
- Better downtime predictability
- Faster issue triage
- Operational coordination across streams

---

# Level 4 — Predictive

## Characteristics
- KPI-driven governance
- Readiness scoring models
- Historical trend analysis
- Predictive operational indicators
- Risk-based prioritization

## Capabilities
- Defect trend forecasting
- Stabilization prediction
- SLA breach anticipation
- Cutover risk exposure scoring

---

# Level 5 — Adaptive

## Characteristics
- AI-assisted orchestration
- Autonomous operational analytics
- Dynamic dependency validation
- Intelligent escalation models
- Continuous operational telemetry

## Vision
An intelligent go-live ecosystem capable of anticipating operational instability before business impact occurs.

---

# Core Maturity Dimensions

The framework evaluates maturity across multiple operational dimensions.

| Dimension | Focus |
|---|---|
| Governance | Executive control and decision structure |
| Cutover Management | Execution orchestration and dependency control |
| Hypercare | Stabilization and support governance |
| Risk Management | Operational risk visibility and mitigation |
| Testing & Quality | Readiness and defect containment |
| Operational Readiness | Business preparedness and continuity |
| Executive Reporting | Decision visibility and escalation clarity |
| Integration Governance | Interface coordination and monitoring |
| Transport Governance | Deployment integrity and control |
| Stabilization Capability | Production recovery and operational resilience |

---

# Operational Metrics That Matter

Traditional project metrics are insufficient during go-live.

This framework emphasizes operational indicators that directly affect production stability.

## Key Metrics

| Metric | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Stabilization Index | Measures recovery speed after go-live |
| Defect Leakage | Measures escaped defects reaching production |
| Business Readiness Score | Evaluates organizational preparedness |
| SLA Adherence | Tracks hypercare responsiveness |
| Cutover Risk Exposure | Measures cumulative deployment risk |
| Incident Reopen Rate | Measures resolution quality |
| Transport Failure Rate | Tracks deployment reliability |
| Mean Time to Stabilization (MTTS) | Measures stabilization efficiency |

---

# Common Signals of a Failed Go-Live

Most go-live failures begin long before production deployment.

## Organizational Signals
- Business users absent from rehearsals
- Undefined escalation ownership
- Hypercare staffing uncertainty
- Executive visibility gaps

## Technical Signals
- Increasing transport backlog near freeze
- High defect aging
- Unresolved integration defects
- Failed rehearsal cycles

## Governance Signals
- Subjective Go/No-Go decisions
- Missing rollback accountability
- Lack of operational readiness scoring

---

# Executive Perspective

Organizations with mature go-live capabilities:
- stabilize faster
- reduce operational disruption
- improve executive confidence
- lower long-term support costs
- increase transformation scalability

The objective is not simply deploying SAP successfully.

The objective is building a repeatable transformation execution capability.

